 debates on imperial relations, colonialism and empire with emerging work on mobility. In doing this, it traces how the movements of people, representations and commodities helped to constitute the British empire from the late-eighteenth century through to the Second World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aBritish Empire.  aImperial history.  aImperialism.  aInfrastructure.  aMigration.  aMobility history.  aMobility studies.  aNineteenth Century.  aRepresentation.  aTransport history.1 aAtkinson, Justine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeborne, Catharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCresswell, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Huw J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Nuala C, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeighren, Innes M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMahony, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerriman, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerriman, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMillward, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester